      "writtenOn": "2026-03-12T03:57:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Updated the section to give more detail regarding the complexity of using Boost.Beast comparing to using sdbusplus with libcurl:\n\n\u003e Boost.Beast is an alternative HTTP library that the daemon can utilize. However,\nsince this library is built on top of Boost.Asio, it uses\n`boost::asio::awaitable\u003cT\u003e` driven by `boost::asio::io_context`, while sdbusplus\nuses stdexec\u0027s sender/receiver pattern with `exec::task\u003c\u003e` driven by\n`execution::run_loop`. These two coroutine types are not interchangeable — a\n`boost::asio::awaitable\u003cT\u003e` cannot be `co_await`ed inside an `exec::task\u003c\u003e`, and\nvice versa. To bridge the two, one would need to run a separate `io_context` on\nan additional thread and use an `eventfd` with `sdbusplus::async::fdio` to\nsignal completion across event loops. This adds an extra thread for Asio\u0027s event\nloop, requires manual signaling to bridge completion across event loops, and\nintroduces thread-safety concerns when shuttling results between threads. In\ncontrast, libcurl with `curl_multi_waitfds` integrates naturally with sdbusplus\nby providing file descriptors that can be monitored directly via\n`sdbusplus::async::fdio`, requiring no extra threads or event loop bridging.",
      "parentUuid": "81cba8da_f3a03eb8",
      "revId": "c2873f82fb4e7c2b609a49ba290b5222fd934ff8",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
